{"title": "Tongues of Conscience", "description": "Tongues of Conscience (1898) is a collection of five thought-provoking stories where an innocent, but selfish, action leads to horrific consequences. Robert Hichens writes some wonderfully evocative descriptions of nature: from a raw and exposed violent seascape, to the serene and idyllic countryside \u201c\u2026the violets seemed to sing in odours\u2026\u201d , to a train pushing through the white-out of a blizzard.<br /><br />\nIn Sea Change an artist with a dark secret (\u201c\u2026I painted for him in words, the varying colors of waves in different seas\u2026 I drowned little Jack in the sea.\u201d) shares the details of his guilt with a priest who tells a simple white lie in an effort to save his tortured friend\u2019s sanity. In \u201cWilliam Foster\u201d, the works of an author rouses his own wife\u2019s religious nature with a most shocking result. In The Cry of the Child a gifted but egotistic doctor is haunted by the wail of his dead baby, but finds salvation with the sacrifice of someone else\u2019s most selfless act. In How Love Came to Professor Guildea a scientist whose research has done wonderful things for humanity, confronts the terror of finding himelf loved. And finally, in The Lady and the Beggar, a wealthy woman\u2019s will leaves her bounty to the poor, but only after she learns a very expensive lesson.\n. - Summary by LisaR", "duration": 31413, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "1811", "name": "Robert Smythe Hichens"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/tongues_of_conscience_1602_librivox/tongues_conscience_1602.jpg", "copyright_year": "1900", "genres": ["Horror & Supernatural Fiction", "Single Author Collections"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "Lisa Reichert"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "Lisa Reichert"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "Amy Gramour"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "Bernd Ungerer"}], "sections": [{"section": 1, "title": "Sea C